The boy who says that he is going to be a man has the noblest ambition in life. There was more or less sense in the story of Diogenes who went through the streets of Athens looking for a man, and in the days of Jerenliah, Jerusalem lacked men that were men as much as did Athens. ''The divine idea of man is given in the scrip- tures. But the external surroundings of a man are often confounded with the true estimate of him. His social position makes a picture frame, as it were, to set off his advantages and to cover up his inner nature. ''The divine idea of a man is one who seeks the truth and does the right. Truth i& sur- rounded by a dense cloud of falsehood and a man must penetrate this mist of unbelief. The spirit of Christ cleanses man from moral impurity and gives hitn a clearer conception of God. The honest man is reliable and is not vacillating in his ideas of moral right. It requires a true man to be honest against his own interests. Doing right is truth in action. The honest 1nan is kept in the steady course of consistent upright- ness. \ We need men in political circles like Clay, who said, ' I would rather be right than presi- dent.'
